<p><b>Multi-monitor</b>, also known as <b>Multi-display</b>, <b>Multi-head</b> and <b>Dual-Monitor</b> are synonymous terms referring to the use of multiple physical <a href="/wiki/Computer_display" title="Computer display" class="mw-redirect">display devices</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Computer_display" title="Computer display" class="mw-redirect">monitors</a>, televisions and <a href="/wiki/Projector" title="Projector">projectors</a> in order to increase the area available for <a href="/wiki/Computer_program" title="Computer program">computer programs</a> running on a single <a href="/wiki/Computer" title="Computer">computer</a> system. <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a> describes this setup as "one of the best ways to improve your productivity".<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Pausch" title="Pausch" class="mw-redirect">Randy Pausch</a> recommended multiple monitors for improving personal productivity in his Time Management lecture.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
